description:
In upgrading my testing cluster from juno to kilo-rc1 on Ubuntu 14.04 I noticed that some of the new columns weren't being populated in my postgres database. I believe I've traced it back to nova-manage not actually writing anything to the database. Pointing it to a new, blank database results in the database still being empty. Other services such as glance and neutron have upgraded fine, so it seems to be limited to nova. I've manually upgraded my sqlalchemy from 0.9.8 to 1.0.2, but to no avail.

title: nova-manage db sync seems like its pointing at the wrong database for some people

comments.content:
In upgrading my testing cluster from juno to kilo-rc1 on Ubuntu 14.04 I noticed that some of the new columns weren't being populated in my postgres database. I believe I've traced it back to nova-manage not actually writing anything to the database. Pointing it to a new, blank database results in the database still being empty. Other services such as glance and neutron have upgraded fine, it's just nova that seems to be causing problems. I've manually upgraded my sqlalchemy from 0.9.8 to 1.0.2, but to no avail.
